Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 33rd Weekly Dose of Optimism. With the=
 struggles at Silicon Valley Bank, things are as shaky in the markets as th=
ey=E2=80=99ve been in a while. So let=E2=80=99s zoom out and take a look at=
 all the good things happening out there.
If you enjoy receiving this newsletter each Friday, please share it with a =
friend or post about us on your platform of choice. We think we=E2=80=99re =
onto something with this whole optimism thing, and now it=E2=80=99s just a =
matter of getting the word out.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6Pesto [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/0e17f008-7e2d-43d6-ad48-734a2fe14c73?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Pesto [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e17f008-7e2d-43d6-ad48-734a2fe14c73?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] helps =
you attract, curate, and manage top global developer talent =E2=80=94 with =
no upfront cost to your team. Companies like Rippling, Google, and Polygon =
rely on Pesto [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e17f008-7e2d-43d6-ad48-734a2=
fe14c73?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] to source top-tier, affordable developer talent from overseas.=20
We=E2=80=99d hope you agree that talent is equally distributed, but opportu=
nity is not. Europe, India & some parts of Africa have great tech talent bu=
t it=E2=80=99s a headache to find, interview, and hire them. You need to do=
 recruiting, vetting, interviewing, and overcome time-zone and language bar=
riers. That=E2=80=99s where Pesto [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e17f008-=
7e2d-43d6-ad48-734a2fe14c73?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] comes in.
With Pesto, you can hire pre-vetted developers at a fraction of the cost an=
d in just 3 weeks. Here=E2=80=99s the cool part: Pesto does Boba Onboarding=
: they ship you a boba bubble tea during your onboarding session and make s=
ure you=E2=80=99ve scheduled interviews with developers before you can fini=
sh the boba. Exclusive offer: Pesto [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e17f00=
8-7e2d-43d6-ad48-734a2fe14c73?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is offering Not Boring readers 50% off their first =
developer hire=E2=80=A6plus, of course, free boba.
(1) The Scientific Breakthrough That Could Make Batteries Last Longer [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/0b10cbc3-b103-4109-85cf-67f125dca635?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Aylin Woodward [ https://substack.com/redirect/0eaf04d7-2cff-4307-bf63-7a9e=
93fd94f8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] for the The Wall Street Journal
U.S. scientists say they have produced the first commercially=C2=A0accessib=
le material that eliminates the loss of energy as electricity moves along a=
 wire, a breakthrough that could=C2=A0mean longer-lasting batteries, more-e=
fficient power grids and improved high-speed trains.
Another step towards energy abundance, this time in materials science. A te=
am of research scientists from the University of Rochester published their =
findings on superconductivity in  [ https://substack.com/redirect/b28b7059-=
9eba-4e14-9a48-b300bee970c4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]Nature [ https://substack.com/redirect/b28b7059-9eba-4=
e14-9a48-b300bee970c4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ] this week. The breakthrough makes superconductivity commerc=
ially viable within the decade.
So what does superconductivity mean? It=E2=80=99s a phenomenon in which mat=
erials exhibit zero electrical resistance and perfect diamagnetism at tempe=
ratures close to absolute zero, allowing for the efficient transmission of =
electrical current with zero energy loss. The breakthrough from Dr. Dias=E2=
=80=99 lab is that the materials it created can be deployed in normal tempe=
ratures and with much less pressure applied.
So what will the commercialization of superconductivity looks like? Longer =
lasting batteries in our devices, long distance EVs, more efficient powergr=
ids, better magnets used in nuclear reactors, and the list goes on.
As a bonus, superconductivity also demonstrates what is called the Meissner=
 effect, which is when a material expels its magnetic field. Put a supercon=
ductor near a magnet, and it will levitate.
(2) US, EU to launch talks on free-trade-like status, easing EV trade dispu=
te [ https://substack.com/redirect/ea5d007a-b8e6-4c0b-b05e-0141f875067e?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Andrea Shalal [ https://substack.com/redirect/0db8d3b0-5e27-4e82-818b-fcf7e=
d04f366?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] and David Shepardson [ https://substack.com/redirect/528a38d9-c615-4cab-8=
34a-35c1281f6522?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ] for Reuters
U.S. President Joe Biden and European Commission President Ursula von der L=
eyen are expected to agree on Friday to begin negotiations on ensuring free=
-trade agreement-like status for the European Union=E2=80=A6Working with al=
lies to reduce U.S. reliance on China for critical minerals would aid U.S. =
energy and economic security, the spokesperson added.
Brandon at it again with the diplomacy. This time, President Biden is tight=
ening relations with the EU in order to sure up the U.S.=E2=80=99 critical =
mineral supply chain. Remember how we just mentioned the importance of mate=
rial science in the story above? Well it turns out, those rare minerals are=
 sourced from around the world. Historically, the U.S. has relied pretty he=
avily on China for mineral sourcing, but as the Second Cold War heats up th=
e Biden Administration is looking to wean off of this China dependency.
Geopolitics aside, we support the Biden Administration=E2=80=99s focus on s=
trengthening (or at least lowering dependencies) supply chains and investin=
g in clean energy technologies. We, of course, don=E2=80=99t blindly suppor=
t everything the Administration does or believes, but a story like this, wh=
ich lies at the intersection of supply chains and clean energy, is somethin=
g we can get behind.
(3) ERC-4337 Explainer
thirdweb [ https://substack.com/redirect/b686b8e4-0501-4b5e-b1c1-fd8d25d54f=
ae?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Back in September 2021, a group including Vitalik Buterin submitted an Ethe=
reum Improvement Proposal (EIP), ERC-4337: [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
fa36545c-39f5-479d-8735-cf048fbb796e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]  [ https://substack.com/redirect/fa36545c-39=
f5-479d-8735-cf048fbb796e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]Account Abstraction Using Alt Mempool [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/fa36545c-39f5-479d-8735-c=
f048fbb796e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Last week, at ETHDenver, it w=
ent live.=20
Without going too deep into the details (you can read the thirdweb thread o=
r this one [ https://substack.com/redirect/b3a78ee8-e9fb-4128-9562-a581a705=
d9b3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] o=
r this one [ https://substack.com/redirect/9249f6b7-afbc-4251-b656-2f490f68=
7418?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] o=
r this one [ https://substack.com/redirect/5f35932b-1352-421f-a735-bc3a7f04=
be69?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] o=
r the proposal itself), ERC-4337 allows for Smart Accounts that would solve=
 a lot of the issues with Externally Owned Accounts (EOAs), like your Metam=
ask wallet.
Instead of forcing people to write down their private key or seed phrase an=
d do a bunch of clunky things in order to transact, and leaving them out to=
 dry if they lose that key or seed phrase, wallet and dapp developers can b=
uild in a bunch of features that make the experience feel a lot more like n=
ormal financial products or apps. Think account recovery, transaction limit=
s, improved security, gasless transactions, and subscriptions. It enables a=
ll of that while preserving decentralization.=20
Might seem kind of wonky, but we=E2=80=99re including it here because it ad=
dresses a bunch of problems that web3=E2=80=99s critics argued would force =
either permanently shitty UX or inevitable decentralization. While prices r=
emain depressed, the infrastructure keeps improving.=20
(4) PaLM-E: An Embodied Multimodal Language Model [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/86bcc8ca-19f8-43cd-a4d8-cc07f4ae066f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
We propose embodied language models to directly incorporate real-world cont=
inuous sensor modalities into language models and thereby establish the lin=
k between words and percepts.
LLM =F0=9F=A4=9D Physical World.
A team of researchers from Google and the Technical University of Berlin ha=
ve infused a LLM with real-world continuous input. =E2=80=9CPaLM-E=E2=80=9D=
 is the combination of Google=E2=80=99s PaLM (a LLM similar to GPT) and =E2=
=80=9CE,=E2=80=9D which stands for Embodied, or the infusion of the sensory=
 information and robotic control.
Taken together, PaLM-E can perform a variety of tasks in the real-world, wi=
thout the need for retraining. It=E2=80=99s able to learn and operate withi=
n its physical surroundings. Interestingly, PaLM-E also exhibited =E2=80=9C=
positive transfer,=E2=80=9D meaning it takes the skills and knowledge gaine=
d in performing one task and can apply it to a new task. Unlike an old dog,=
 LLMs just keep revealing new tricks.=20
We=E2=80=99re not there yet, but this is a meaningful step towards the crea=
tion of autonomous, human-like robots. AI is already scary good, but as mor=
e multimodal applications roll out, it=E2=80=99ll become more obvious just =
how these technologies will impact our daily lives.
And rumor has it [ https://substack.com/redirect/1c168d1d-aefb-40cd-a3f5-bd=
ceaf2cc28e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] GPT-4 may be dropping next week=E2=80=A6=20
(5) Can money buy happiness? Scientists say it can. [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/58521a9f-b769-47b0-b16a-c5e3c089592e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Adela Suliman [ https://substack.com/redirect/6c9881fd-56f7-4116-892d-40a11=
b274337?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for The Washington Post
Two prominent researchers, Daniel Kahneman and Matthew Killingsworth, came =
to this conclusion in a joint study published [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/7c9dbdc6-a42c-4514-9a94-0537431c7ced?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] this month in the Proceedings of the Nati=
onal Academy of Sciences, overturning the dominant thinking that people are=
 generally happier as they earn more, with their joy leveling out when thei=
r income hits $75,000.
I knew something seemed fishy with that whole =E2=80=9Cmoney can=E2=80=99t =
buy happiness=E2=80=9D mumbo-jumbo. A recent study from Kahneman (yes, that=
 Kahneman) and Killingworth found that =E2=80=9Chappiness continues to rise=
 with income even in the high range of incomes.=E2=80=9D
The main exception to this finding is of course that a certain percentage o=
f people are going to be miserable whether or not they have money, and a pe=
rcentage of those peoples=E2=80=99 misery will only increase as wealth incr=
eases.
While this article is a bit clickbaity, I do think the underlining finding =
on wealth and happiness is important. In fact, it=E2=80=99s one of the cent=
ral ideas driving this whole capitalism thing that we do. If happiness is w=
hat life is all about, and there=E2=80=99s a strong correlation (and perhap=
s causation) between happiness and wealth, then we should continue to pursu=
e innovation that makes more people wealthier. But, the authors caution, =
=E2=80=9Cif you=E2=80=99re rich and miserable, more money won=E2=80=99t hel=
p.=E2=80=9D
